items.headline: ‘Madam Secretary’ Star Jill Hennessy on TV, Politics and Her Music

headlines.web: ‘Madam Secretary’ Star Jill Hennessy on TV, Politics and Her Music

lede.caption: Jill Hennessy got her start in television as Assistant District Attorney Claire Kincaid on the NBC hit "Law & Order," holding her own opposite the great Sam Waterston. She went on to headline "Crossing Jordan" for the network, and most recently kicked off a recurring role on CBS's "Madam Secretary," as a "defense intelligence agency handler." All the while, Hennessy has kept up a double life as a rock 'n' roller, releasing her second album, "I Do," just last week. John Heilemann sat down Hennessy to talk about her career playing political roles and how she balances it with her musical ambitions.

lede.caption: Approximately 45 million members of the media filed into the Wynn hotel media room Tuesday night to cover the Democratic debate in Las Vegas. items.summary: Approximately 45 million members of the media filed into the Wynn hotel media room on Tuesday night to cover the Democratic presidential debate in Las Vegas. It wasn't as exciting as the Republican debates have been, but thankfully Donald Trump swooped in at the last minute to live-tweet the whole thing. So we ditched the Democrats and drove to nearby Henderson, Nevada, where the state GOP was hosting a watch party. There was Little Caesar's pizza, dueling campaign booths, and more than enough Republicans happy to read Trump's tweets on camera in real time. (By Griffin Hammond and Matt Negrin)

items.headline: Donald Trump Loves His Bible and Christmas Too

headlines.web: Donald Trump Loves His Bible and Christmas Too

lede.caption: Billionaire GOP hopeful Donald Trump addressed the annual Values Voter Summit today in Washington. The candidate, who’s had some recent struggles explaining his faith, brought his childhood Bible for all to see. "I believe in God," he said. "I believe in the Bible. I’m Christian. I love people." He lashed out against political correctness, asking the audience, “Remember the expression 'Merry Christmas?' You don't see it. You're going to see it if I'm elected."
